docs.abstract: Tech companies and their employees love big cities, but Amazon needs to do better for people who live in any city chosen for its second headquarters.
docs.snippet: Tech companies and their employees love big cities, but Amazon needs to do better for people who live in any city chosen for its second headquarters.
docs.lead_paragraph: The prune capital of America. That was the future Silicon Valley’s greatest claim to fame in the 1920s, when it was a sleepy landscape of fruit orchards and farms far removed from the nation’s industrial might. Seattle was a city of fishing and timber, where a young entrepreneur named Bill Boeing had so few customers for his airplanes that he briefly pivoted to making furniture. The most innovative companies in the world clustered in the ferociously inventive cities of the East and Midwest — cars in Detroit; cash registers in Dayton, Ohio; light bulbs in Cleveland.

headline.main: A Warning From Seattle to Amazon’s HQ2

docs.abstract: Many in the tech industry don’t want to be part of the military-industrial complex. But defense work is already part of Silicon Valley’s DNA.
docs.snippet: Many in the tech industry don’t want to be part of the military-industrial complex. But defense work is already part of Silicon Valley’s DNA.
docs.lead_paragraph: The sunny precincts of Silicon Valley have been wrestling for months with the question of whether technology companies should stay out of work related to the military. Google recently announced that it would no longer compete for a $10 billion Pentagon cloud computing contract. Microsoft employees have pressured its chief executive to do the same.

headline.main: Silicon Valley Can’t Escape the Business of War
